{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01T7cVu8SzxDPfEbULsS8izx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No protoc available. I need to update the proto source file AND manually update the generated Go files. Since the generated pb files already have `OrchestrateRequest` and `OrchestrateResponse` (even though the source proto doesn't), someone has been editing these manually or regenerating from a different proto version.\n\nFor the `OrchestrateResponse`, I need to add a `run_id` field. The cleanest approach without protoc is to add it as a regular Go field. Since gRPC serializes via protobuf, I actually need to update the protobuf raw descriptor bytes too for proper wire serialization.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. \n\nThe Go struct fields and raw descriptor need to stay in sync—if I only add the field to the struct without updating the descriptor, protobuf won't serialize it and the run_id gets silently dropped over the wire. Without protoc to regenerate everything, my options are limited: I could avoid adding new protobuf fields entirely and instead reuse an existing field like `Dispatched` to signal success, or find another way to communicate the run_id without modifying the protobuf schema.\n\nActually, I'm overthinking this—the CLI just needs to show that orchestration started. I can make the server actually launch the workflow, return `Dispatched: 1` to confirm it worked, and update the CLI message to say \"Started orchestration for <project>.\" The run_id would be nice to have, but I could work around that. Let me try installing protoc and regenerating the code properly instead of hacking around the schema. a `RunId` field. For gRPC over local IPC (unix socket), both client and server are using the same binary/code. The protobuf wire format supports unknown fields, so adding a field to the struct that isn't in the descriptor won't cause errors - it just won't be serialized.\n\nHmm wait, that means the run_id would be lost in transit. That's a problem.\n\nOK, let me think about this differently. The approach used in the existing codebase is that generated pb files already contain Orchestrate RPC that doesn't match the proto source. So clearly they're OK with editing generated files.\n\nFor the run_id, I have a few options:\n1. Install protoc and regenerate\n2. Manually edit the raw descriptor bytes in pb.go (very error-prone)\n3. Don't return run_id, just output a message\n\nLet me go with installing protoc and regenerating the files.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":105,"cache_read_input_tokens":48249,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":105},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e86d396b-c477-4111-8724-c79fdb5bf532","uuid":"845360db-edf0-4a7d-b1d3-1af51b349c1d"}
